        Chart Review 22/11/24

        Ignore what the top of this comment says. There isn't a review this week, or the next, obviously because I'm on holiday in the Canary Islands wondering if this is the cause of why my homework assignments are going AWOL on me. I was also coming home from a massive water park called Aqualand, so I clearly couldn't have written this review in time. But in short, it's a brilliant day for guitar music, as Linkin Park's new album casually thrusts it's three eligible hits up the chart, and joining them in Top 10 heaven is Sam Fender, a.k.a. Newcastle's answer to Bruce Springsteen, but with added saxophone. It's about time he didn't turn out to be a one-hit wonder.

        Anyways, the Christmas songs are taking over as Wham! and Brenda Lee join Mariah to clog up Alexa playlists across the land. See you next time when Kendrick Lamar's surprise new album he dropped today (definitely not because he's doing the next Super Bowl) malfunctions the rap world for the rest of 2024.

        What's particularly tedious about the annual "Christmas takeover", aside from it taking up an ever higher percentage of the chart, is it isn't even our own.

        The generic, curated Spotify playlists, which will supply the vast majority of these streams (rather than anyone actually picking out any of these songs by choice, heaven forbid), will be stuffed with Fifties and Sixties US hits that never even did anything over here, presumably because Spotify is based over there. Which means the seasonal soundtrack is now increasingly dominated by them other than the ever-more lopsided volume of streams going to Last Christmas (hitting its 100th chart week this week), which even Mariah hasn't been able to touch the last couple of years... something that's got boring in its own right, but that's another story.

        Things like even the biggest glam-era British classics (Slade, Wizzard, Mud etc) can barely get a look-in these last 6 or 7 years. Whereas mid-century transatlantic stuff like the songs from Brenda Lee (unseen in the Top 40 from 1963-2017), Bobby Helms (never a hit before 2017, his only previous chart appearances of any sort were in 1957-58), Andy Williams (only a downland-era hit in 2007, then streaming post-2017), Dean Martin (first nudged the Top 40 in the last week of 2019) and the Ronettes (ditto) are now routinely leading the pack trailing behind Wham! and Mariah.

        It's like we've suddenly lost the UK's own Christmas tradition, and instead are now drowning in some ersatz nostalgia for a 1950s American Christmas we never actually had.


        (Oh, and it looks like even Mr Brightside (no.90 in its 437th chart appearance) is about to get turfed out of the Top 100 next week, after its mandated 47 annual weeks of continuous residency. I'll await its inevitable return in five weeks' time for the next 47.)

        H
